nt of   Dinan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dinan","meanings":["Irish (now mainly counties Clare and Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Daghnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Daghnán</i>’, possibly a diminutive of <i>dagh</i> ‘good’.","Irish: variant of   Dineen  .","French: habitational name from Dinan, in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwaeddan ap Cynan was born about 1364, in Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cynan \"Felyn\" ap Gwrgeneu, was 236 and his mother, Mrs. Cynan Felyn ap Gwrgeneu, was 232. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Gwaeddan ap Cynan."},"et":{"about 1364–":"umbes 1364–Surnud","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1368–Female":"1368–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1134–Female":"1134–Surnud","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1368":"1368","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","1364":"1364","1130":"1130","about 1364":"umbes 1364","1390":"1390","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1364–":"noin 1364–Kuollut","1156–Female":"1156–Kuollut","1364–Male":"1364–Kuollut","1368–Female":"1368–Kuollut","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1134–Female":"1134–Kuollut","about 1390":"noin 1390","1368":"1368","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","1364":"1364","1130":"1130","about 1364":"noin 1364","1390":"1390","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1364–":"environ 1364–Décédé","1156–Female":"1156–Décédée","1364–Male":"1364–Décédé","1368–Female":"1368–Décédée","1390–Male":"1390–Décédé","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1134–Female":"1134–Décédée","about 1390":"environ 1390","1368":"1368","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","1364":"1364","1130":"1130","about 1364":"environ 1364","1390":"1390","of,,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Gwaeddan ap Cynan est né environ 1364, à Radnorshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, s